00:40:10.740 --> 00:40:15.510
I want to multiply row 2 by some
number and subtract from row 1

00:40:15.510 --> 00:40:17.310
and get that 0.

00:40:17.310 --> 00:40:19.590
So what do I multiply row 2 by?

00:40:19.590 --> 00:40:20.130
AUDIENCE: 2.

00:40:20.130 --> 00:40:22.140
GILBERT STRANG: 2, thank you.

00:40:22.140 --> 00:40:24.750
Everybody in this class
is going to have an A.

00:40:24.750 --> 00:40:26.662
[APPLAUSE]

00:40:26.662 --> 00:40:29.530
[CHEERING, APPLAUSE]

00:40:29.530 --> 00:40:32.880


00:40:32.880 --> 00:40:38.550
I'm sorry to think that this
class is recorded, because I

00:40:38.550 --> 00:40:40.050
didn't really mean it.

00:40:40.050 --> 00:40:42.816
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:42.816 --> 00:40:44.200


00:40:44.200 --> 00:40:47.220
I'll just say, you all
deserve an A. How's that?

00:40:47.220 --> 00:40:48.720
That's a nice note.

00:40:48.720 --> 00:40:51.360
Yes, at least based
on so far today,

00:40:51.360 --> 00:40:53.950
but there's more questions
on this final exam.

00:40:53.950 --> 00:40:57.220
So you have A so far.

00:40:57.220 --> 00:40:57.720
OK.

00:40:57.720 --> 00:41:02.130
So I want to subtract this from
the row above to get that 0.

00:41:02.130 --> 00:41:04.470
What do I multiply this by?

00:41:04.470 --> 00:41:05.280
2.

00:41:05.280 --> 00:41:08.040
Subtract from this,
so 2 1's is 2,

00:41:08.040 --> 00:41:09.780
and the subtraction gives the 0.

00:41:09.780 --> 00:41:13.710
2 4's is 8, leaving 3.

00:41:13.710 --> 00:41:17.760
And 2 6's is 12, leaving 5.

00:41:17.760 --> 00:41:19.890
OK.

00:41:19.890 --> 00:41:23.920
So my equation is now--

00:41:23.920 --> 00:41:26.220
my three equations are--

00:41:26.220 --> 00:41:28.840
well, this is a
0-equals-0 equation.

00:41:28.840 --> 00:41:37.840
My equations are x1 from
the 1, no x2s, three x3's,

00:41:37.840 --> 00:41:42.840
and five x4s equaling 0.

00:41:42.840 --> 00:41:45.840
The right side stayed 0
because it was always there.

00:41:45.840 --> 00:41:52.300
And the other equation
here is no x1's, 1 x2,

00:41:52.300 --> 00:41:56.920
4 x3's, and 6 x4's.

00:41:56.920 --> 00:41:59.860


00:41:59.860 --> 00:42:02.110
OK.

00:42:02.110 --> 00:42:07.450
So those equations are
equivalent to the first ones.

00:42:07.450 --> 00:42:11.110
I just did subtraction of
equation from equation.

00:42:11.110 --> 00:42:14.560
That's totally safe,
and it's reversible.

00:42:14.560 --> 00:42:18.100
I could get from that back
to that by doing adding back.

00:42:18.100 --> 00:42:23.920
So that's just as good and, in
fact, better than the original.

00:42:23.920 --> 00:42:26.800
We ought to be
able to write down

00:42:26.800 --> 00:42:28.960
the solutions for this one.

00:42:28.960 --> 00:42:31.810
And let me count--
what are we expecting?

00:42:31.810 --> 00:42:34.600
Let's get a little
geometry in this.

00:42:34.600 --> 00:42:39.690
So I have-- I'm in
four-dimensional space.

00:42:39.690 --> 00:42:42.530
That's a challenge
right away to visualize

00:42:42.530 --> 00:42:44.270
four-dimensional space.

00:42:44.270 --> 00:42:47.210
But I have an x1, x2, x3, x4.

00:42:47.210 --> 00:42:52.120
So my solution vector
has four components.

00:42:52.120 --> 00:42:58.600
And so what are some solutions?

00:42:58.600 --> 00:43:01.840
What are all the solutions
I'd like to know?

00:43:01.840 --> 00:43:05.590
And notice one point,
that there's 0's

00:43:05.590 --> 00:43:07.850
on the right-hand side.

00:43:07.850 --> 00:43:12.900
So that tells me if I find one
set of x's that works, then

00:43:12.900 --> 00:43:15.660
2 times that set
of x's will work.

00:43:15.660 --> 00:43:20.790
5 times that set of x's
will work because it'll just

00:43:20.790 --> 00:43:23.400
multiply all--

00:43:23.400 --> 00:43:27.870
because I'll have 0 equals 0,
and I can safely multiply by 5.

00:43:27.870 --> 00:43:35.050
So I'm expecting two solutions,
two separate solutions.

00:43:35.050 --> 00:43:38.920
And I'll write those
maybe up above.

00:43:38.920 --> 00:43:42.070
x1, x2, x3, x4.

00:43:42.070 --> 00:43:46.250


00:43:46.250 --> 00:43:48.620
Yeah, so give me a--

00:43:48.620 --> 00:43:53.210
so I have two equations,
and for these four unknowns,

00:43:53.210 --> 00:44:04.330
let me start out with a x3 equal
to a 1 and x4 equal to a 0.

00:44:04.330 --> 00:44:10.630
So I'm just sort of freely
setting x3 and x4 as 1 and 0.

00:44:10.630 --> 00:44:12.700
And then I'll figure
out or you'll figure out

00:44:12.700 --> 00:44:15.310
what x1 and x2 have to be.

00:44:15.310 --> 00:44:17.830
So what's the answer, then?

00:44:17.830 --> 00:44:25.550
If x3 is 1 and x4
is 0, what is x1?

00:44:25.550 --> 00:44:27.560
And this is obviously 0.

00:44:27.560 --> 00:44:29.210
So what is x1?

00:44:29.210 --> 00:44:32.375
That leads to x1 equal--

00:44:32.375 --> 00:44:35.550


00:44:35.550 --> 00:44:36.660
what x1?

00:44:36.660 --> 00:44:38.100
AUDIENCE: Negative 3.

00:44:38.100 --> 00:44:40.050
GILBERT STRANG:
Negative 3, thank you.

00:44:40.050 --> 00:44:40.920
And what's x2?

00:44:40.920 --> 00:44:43.460


00:44:43.460 --> 00:44:45.590
That will come
from this equation.

00:44:45.590 --> 00:44:47.270
What will x2 be?

00:44:47.270 --> 00:44:48.420
AUDIENCE: Negative 4.

00:44:48.420 --> 00:44:49.545
GILBERT STRANG: Negative 4.

00:44:49.545 --> 00:44:51.800


00:44:51.800 --> 00:44:54.980
So that's a solution.

00:44:54.980 --> 00:44:58.292
We've solved this original
problem-- aw, I erased it.

00:44:58.292 --> 00:45:01.490
It was much worse
at the beginning,

00:45:01.490 --> 00:45:04.170
but we found a solution.

00:45:04.170 --> 00:45:08.610
But again, we have
four unknowns and we

00:45:08.610 --> 00:45:14.310
have only two real equations,
two independent equations,

00:45:14.310 --> 00:45:17.650
because this third equation
turned out to be a fraud.

00:45:17.650 --> 00:45:20.580
It was just a
combination of 1 and 2.

00:45:20.580 --> 00:45:24.100
So we really have only two
equations, four unknowns.

00:45:24.100 --> 00:45:27.000
So we would expect
two solutions,

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:29.050
and I found one of them.

00:45:29.050 --> 00:45:32.360
OK, so that's good.

00:45:32.360 --> 00:45:36.020
So let me find the
other one, and then

00:45:36.020 --> 00:45:38.820
this problem is solved,
and we can go on.

00:45:38.820 --> 00:45:45.320
So another solution-- I want
to find another x1, x2, x3,

00:45:45.320 --> 00:45:52.190
and x4, and tell me
what it-- so this time,

00:45:52.190 --> 00:45:55.600
I'll start with 0
and 1 for these guys.

00:45:55.600 --> 00:45:58.420
I'll let that be
0 and that be 1.

00:45:58.420 --> 00:46:02.770
And then I'll use the
equations to tell me x1 and x2,

00:46:02.770 --> 00:46:04.890
or you will.

00:46:04.890 --> 00:46:08.205
So now what is x1
from this equation?

00:46:08.205 --> 00:46:09.450
AUDIENCE: Minus 5.

00:46:09.450 --> 00:46:11.760
GILBERT STRANG: Minus 5, thanks.

00:46:11.760 --> 00:46:13.890
This is minus 5.

00:46:13.890 --> 00:46:17.724
And what is x2
from this equation?

00:46:17.724 --> 00:46:20.088
AUDIENCE: Negative--

00:46:20.088 --> 00:46:21.130
GILBERT STRANG: Negative?

00:46:21.130 --> 00:46:21.545
AUDIENCE: 6.

00:46:21.545 --> 00:46:21.960
AUDIENCE: Negative 6.

00:46:21.960 --> 00:46:23.220
GILBERT STRANG: Negative 6.

00:46:23.220 --> 00:46:28.350
OK, we found two solutions,
clearly independent-- minus 3,

00:46:28.350 --> 00:46:30.450
minus 4, 1, 0.

00:46:30.450 --> 00:46:32.430
That's a vector in
four dimensions.

00:46:32.430 --> 00:46:33.720
We're in four dimensions.

00:46:33.720 --> 00:46:36.810


00:46:36.810 --> 00:46:40.290
Linear algebra has no problem
to go up in dimension.

00:46:40.290 --> 00:46:41.700
It stays linear.

00:46:41.700 --> 00:46:43.470
That's what keeps things simple.

00:46:43.470 --> 00:46:46.350
And then it goes up to
any number of dimensions.

00:46:46.350 --> 00:46:49.680
And so these would
be typical problems

00:46:49.680 --> 00:46:56.420
coming from some
engineering system, some--

00:46:56.420 --> 00:46:59.280


00:46:59.280 --> 00:47:03.430
yeah, so we have two solutions,
and that's somehow right.

00:47:03.430 --> 00:47:07.100
And any combination of
those is a solution.

00:47:07.100 --> 00:47:08.860
So I have actually--

00:47:08.860 --> 00:47:13.420
if I combine one of this
solution plus 6 of that

00:47:13.420 --> 00:47:16.930
solution, I'd have another
solution because, on the right

00:47:16.930 --> 00:47:20.230
side, I would just
have still all 0's.

00:47:20.230 --> 00:47:26.350
OK, so that problem is solved,
that for, and that, as we

00:47:26.350 --> 00:47:27.340
expected.

00:47:27.340 --> 00:47:29.720
And let's just review.

00:47:29.720 --> 00:47:38.510
So I have-- I started with
three rows and four columns.

00:47:38.510 --> 00:47:42.470
But the three rows
were not independent.

00:47:42.470 --> 00:47:45.380
The three equations-- a
combination of the three

00:47:45.380 --> 00:47:47.060
equations gave me a 0.

00:47:47.060 --> 00:47:51.170
So I really had the
rank of the matrix is 2.

00:47:51.170 --> 00:48:00.530
So this is a matrix with m
equal 3 rows, n equal 4 columns,

00:48:00.530 --> 00:48:06.890
but the rank of
the matrix is what?

00:48:06.890 --> 00:48:11.420
Now, everybody, if you don't
know what the word "rank" is,

00:48:11.420 --> 00:48:13.820
let the 18.06 tell you.

00:48:13.820 --> 00:48:15.900
What's the rank of my matrix?

00:48:15.900 --> 00:48:16.400
AUDIENCE: 2.

00:48:16.400 --> 00:48:17.930
GILBERT STRANG: 2,
oh, you do know.

00:48:17.930 --> 00:48:18.680
Yeah, OK.

00:48:18.680 --> 00:48:19.970
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHS]

00:48:19.970 --> 00:48:22.240
GILBERT STRANG:
So its rank is 2.

00:48:22.240 --> 00:48:24.880
So its row rank is 2.

00:48:24.880 --> 00:48:28.593
Now the most wonderful
theorem in linear algebra--

00:48:28.593 --> 00:48:30.260
and the most wonderful
theorem, at least

00:48:30.260 --> 00:48:32.180
at the beginning
of linear algebra,

00:48:32.180 --> 00:48:36.950
is that if I have two
independent rows--

00:48:36.950 --> 00:48:39.500
and that's what I have,
two independent rows.

00:48:39.500 --> 00:48:42.620
The third row was a
combination, didn't count.

00:48:42.620 --> 00:48:46.340
So I had two independent
rows, so the row rank is 2.

00:48:46.340 --> 00:48:48.720
And now look at the columns.

00:48:48.720 --> 00:48:51.140
So I had originally
four columns.

00:48:51.140 --> 00:48:52.940
I still have four columns.

00:48:52.940 --> 00:48:55.640
I didn't mess with combinations.

00:48:55.640 --> 00:49:00.710
How many independent
columns do I have?

00:49:00.710 --> 00:49:04.700
How many-- yeah,
look at this matrix.

00:49:04.700 --> 00:49:06.490
Look at this matrix,
because nothing--

00:49:06.490 --> 00:49:08.600
these numbers didn't change.

00:49:08.600 --> 00:49:09.650
Look at that matrix.

00:49:09.650 --> 00:49:16.340
So that has 1, 2, 3, 4 columns,
but they're not independent.

00:49:16.340 --> 00:49:20.970
Some of those columns are
combinations of other columns.

00:49:20.970 --> 00:49:24.180
That's what the beginning
of linear algebra is about.

00:49:24.180 --> 00:49:28.770
And what's the answer
to the column rank?

00:49:28.770 --> 00:49:33.050
So the column rank is the
number of independent columns.

00:49:33.050 --> 00:49:35.390
And what do I get for that?

00:49:35.390 --> 00:49:36.590
AUDIENCE: 2.

00:49:36.590 --> 00:49:38.000
GILBERT STRANG: 2, thank you.

00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:41.090
That's a great,
first, wonderful,

00:49:41.090 --> 00:49:43.880
not-at-all-clear fact.

00:49:43.880 --> 00:49:46.880
If I went back to
the original matrix

00:49:46.880 --> 00:49:49.670
and said there are
two independent rows,

00:49:49.670 --> 00:49:55.550
and then math told me that there
were two independent columns,

00:49:55.550 --> 00:49:59.810
well, I would believe it
because it gets proved in 18.06,

00:49:59.810 --> 00:50:06.050
but this is a great fact, that
the number of independent rows

00:50:06.050 --> 00:50:09.160
matches the number of
independent columns.

