And today, when I know that my
son is outside playing soccer,

00:54:33.200 --> 00:54:37.250
and I hear the sound
of shattering glass,

00:54:37.250 --> 00:54:38.240
I close my eyes.

00:54:38.240 --> 00:54:41.390
I take a deep breath, and
I go to my good place,

00:54:41.390 --> 00:54:42.590
which is your office.

00:54:42.590 --> 00:54:43.720
[LAUGHTER]

00:54:43.720 --> 00:54:45.860
That's the safe place.

00:54:45.860 --> 00:54:47.030
That's the safe place in me.

00:54:47.030 --> 00:54:50.360
So you've been--

00:54:50.360 --> 00:54:53.610
Alan was saying
something to that effect,

00:54:53.610 --> 00:54:57.770
but you've been a role model
in all aspects of my life.

00:54:57.770 --> 00:54:59.690
You've taught me
a lot of things.

00:54:59.690 --> 00:55:01.670
You've taught me--
you've shown me

00:55:01.670 --> 00:55:05.750
how to give without
thinking about taking.

00:55:05.750 --> 00:55:10.220
You taught me how to
always find a positive way

00:55:10.220 --> 00:55:12.560
when you need to say
something and how

00:55:12.560 --> 00:55:15.470
it's especially important to
find a positive way to answer

00:55:15.470 --> 00:55:18.530
a question that wasn't
necessarily asked

00:55:18.530 --> 00:55:21.890
in a positive way.

00:55:21.890 --> 00:55:25.970
You taught me a lot about always
remembering about what matters.

00:55:25.970 --> 00:55:31.220
I remember I was lamenting
to you how my videos--

00:55:31.220 --> 00:55:35.240
how other math videos on YouTube
get thousands of times more

00:55:35.240 --> 00:55:37.280
views than my videos.

00:55:37.280 --> 00:55:42.250
And you said, views, yes,
but how many memories?

00:55:42.250 --> 00:55:48.230
And I just want to say that guys
are so lucky because you will

00:55:48.230 --> 00:55:52.820
remember this class, and you
will remember this experience,

00:55:52.820 --> 00:55:54.350
and you will have
these memories,

00:55:54.350 --> 00:55:58.250
and thanks for teaching me that
it's the memories that count

00:55:58.250 --> 00:55:59.120
and not the views.

00:55:59.120 --> 00:56:03.530
And I never thought about views
again after that conversation.

00:56:03.530 --> 00:56:08.060
Now, you also-- what
I really appreciate

00:56:08.060 --> 00:56:11.150
is that you're always
forthcoming with advice

00:56:11.150 --> 00:56:12.630
when it's badly needed.

00:56:12.630 --> 00:56:15.290
And I'll just relate one story.

00:56:15.290 --> 00:56:18.170
When you were over at
our house for dinner

00:56:18.170 --> 00:56:21.680
and you learned that my kitchen
had been under construction

00:56:21.680 --> 00:56:24.560
for a year and making
very slow progress,

00:56:24.560 --> 00:56:27.170
you looked me straight
in the eye and said,

00:56:27.170 --> 00:56:30.350
Pavel, your family
needs a kitchen.

00:56:30.350 --> 00:56:33.720
And a month later, my
kitchen was completed,

00:56:33.720 --> 00:56:37.610
and I needed to
hear that, and this

00:56:37.610 --> 00:56:40.160
is the mildest of
all examples when

00:56:40.160 --> 00:56:43.880
you recognize that I
needed input from you,

00:56:43.880 --> 00:56:45.330
and you gave it.

00:56:45.330 --> 00:56:48.077
So I'm thankful
for that very much.

00:56:48.077 --> 00:56:49.160
GILBERT STRANG: Thank you.

00:56:49.160 --> 00:56:51.620
PAVEL GRINFELD: And my
wife thanks you too.

00:56:51.620 --> 00:56:54.900
I just have two
more things to say.

00:56:54.900 --> 00:56:57.920
So a few years ago,
you came to Drexel

00:56:57.920 --> 00:57:00.530
and gave a talk at
the Math Colloquium.

00:57:00.530 --> 00:57:04.730
And you said, I'm about to use
two words that I may have never

00:57:04.730 --> 00:57:07.580
used in a talk before,
and those words

00:57:07.580 --> 00:57:10.460
were "theorem" and
"proof," which is quite

00:57:10.460 --> 00:57:12.410
remarkable for a mathematician.

00:57:12.410 --> 00:57:15.200
And I think we all
appreciate how you

00:57:15.200 --> 00:57:17.630
keep things unsophisticated.

00:57:17.630 --> 00:57:19.675
Just look at this board--

00:57:19.675 --> 00:57:23.670
its clear, clear,
and clear and simple.

00:57:23.670 --> 00:57:28.668
And for a guy who only
talks about matrices,

00:57:28.668 --> 00:57:30.960
it's amazing that you are,
as I see it, one of the most

00:57:30.960 --> 00:57:33.210
universal mathematicians.

00:57:33.210 --> 00:57:36.750
And you have taught us
that a simple 3-by-3 matrix

00:57:36.750 --> 00:57:41.740
can give us scientific insight.

00:57:41.740 --> 00:57:46.060
And before you, "matrix"
was a dirty word.

00:57:46.060 --> 00:57:49.330
And now I think we would
all be proud to have

00:57:49.330 --> 00:57:52.390
a beautiful matrix
with special properties

00:57:52.390 --> 00:57:55.030
at the center of
any of our papers.

00:57:55.030 --> 00:57:56.980
And I think that
mathematicians used

00:57:56.980 --> 00:58:01.240
to look down on linear algebra,
but you were right all along

00:58:01.240 --> 00:58:03.250
about how important
the subject is.

00:58:03.250 --> 00:58:07.630
And I think ChatGPT and the
linear algebra behind it

00:58:07.630 --> 00:58:09.220
looks down on us.

00:58:09.220 --> 00:58:11.200
So you had it right.

00:58:11.200 --> 00:58:15.940
So we're all very excited to
see what you will accomplish

00:58:15.940 --> 00:58:21.040
in your retirement, but I'm
sure that whatever it is,

00:58:21.040 --> 00:58:23.710
you will be remembered not
just for your scientific

00:58:23.710 --> 00:58:26.620
accomplishments but
for human decency.

00:58:26.620 --> 00:58:30.770
And I might be biased
because I was your student,

00:58:30.770 --> 00:58:33.177
but I think you were
the best, so thank you.

00:58:33.177 --> 00:58:34.010
[CHEERING, APPLAUSE]

00:58:34.010 --> 00:58:35.093
GILBERT STRANG: Thank you.

00:58:35.093 --> 00:58:42.350


00:58:42.350 --> 00:58:44.115
Thank you, Pavel.

00:58:44.115 --> 00:58:45.365
Thanks, that was really great.

