and I am the head

00:58:59.150 --> 00:59:00.380
of the math department.

00:59:00.380 --> 00:59:05.600
And Gil's career at MIT has
just been extraordinary.

00:59:05.600 --> 00:59:09.800
As he said, he has
been for 61 years

00:59:09.800 --> 00:59:13.400
on the faculty in mathematics.

00:59:13.400 --> 00:59:18.230
And that's actually more
than any other faculty

00:59:18.230 --> 00:59:23.150
member in the history of
the department and possibly

00:59:23.150 --> 00:59:24.320
of the history of--

00:59:24.320 --> 00:59:27.743
[APPLAUSE]

00:59:27.743 --> 00:59:29.210


00:59:29.210 --> 00:59:33.200
--and possibly even in the
history of MIT, but I didn't--

00:59:33.200 --> 00:59:36.960
I couldn't check that.

00:59:36.960 --> 00:59:40.670
And as he said, his
affiliation with MIT

00:59:40.670 --> 00:59:42.680
has been even
longer since he was

00:59:42.680 --> 00:59:49.210
a math major from 1952 to 1955
and a Moore instructor from '59

00:59:49.210 --> 00:59:50.480
to '61.

00:59:50.480 --> 00:59:52.190
Mathematics, as you
know, is everywhere

00:59:52.190 --> 00:59:53.660
in engineering and science.

00:59:53.660 --> 00:59:55.850
And in that spirit,
Gil's mission

00:59:55.850 --> 00:59:58.670
has been to educate
countless of students

00:59:58.670 --> 01:00:02.960
from everywhere on the planet
in linear algebra, calculus,

01:00:02.960 --> 01:00:04.580
differential
equations, and, more

01:00:04.580 --> 01:00:10.250
generally, applied mathematics
and computational science.

01:00:10.250 --> 01:00:12.150
I say everyone on the planet--

01:00:12.150 --> 01:00:14.700
and, in fact, at the
beginning of this lecture,

01:00:14.700 --> 01:00:18.530
I was checking on YouTube,
and I saw comments from people

01:00:18.530 --> 01:00:22.070
in Kurdistan, Turkey, Russia,
Mongolia, Iran, Brazil,

01:00:22.070 --> 01:00:26.060
Thailand, India, South Korea,
Nigeria, Germany, Malaysia,

01:00:26.060 --> 01:00:28.850
Hong Kong, Bangladesh,
Philippines, Morocco, Greece,

01:00:28.850 --> 01:00:33.020
Italy, China, Taiwan, Brazil,
Armenia, Indonesia, Croatia,

01:00:33.020 --> 01:00:37.250
Egypt, and even my own
country of Belgium.

01:00:37.250 --> 01:00:39.800
His lectures are legendary.

01:00:39.800 --> 01:00:44.660
It's not a surprise that 450
students registered for 18.06

01:00:44.660 --> 01:00:46.700
for the last term he
was teaching together

01:00:46.700 --> 01:00:49.010
with Andrew Horning.

01:00:49.010 --> 01:00:54.140
But students well
beyond the walls of MIT

01:00:54.140 --> 01:00:57.560
have benefited from his classes.

01:00:57.560 --> 01:01:04.370
He was the first to
put lectures on OCW

01:01:04.370 --> 01:01:08.900
as it started and has had--

01:01:08.900 --> 01:01:16.700
his many courses on OCW attract
about 5,000 daily visits.

01:01:16.700 --> 01:01:20.840
That's pretty significant.

01:01:20.840 --> 01:01:23.540
And his videos
apparently have been seen

01:01:23.540 --> 01:01:25.790
by more than 14 million people.

01:01:25.790 --> 01:01:29.280
That's quite remarkable.

01:01:29.280 --> 01:01:31.250
And as part of his
educational mission,

01:01:31.250 --> 01:01:36.410
he has published over 17 books,
if I got the number right,

01:01:36.410 --> 01:01:38.450
because it seems
that, every week,

01:01:38.450 --> 01:01:41.060
there is almost a new one.

01:01:41.060 --> 01:01:44.870
His impact on
mathematics has been--

01:01:44.870 --> 01:01:46.940
and especially on
math education,

01:01:46.940 --> 01:01:48.840
has been mind boggling.

01:01:48.840 --> 01:01:51.320
So I taught 18.06
many years ago.

01:01:51.320 --> 01:01:54.950
And before teaching, I
attended Gil's lectures just

01:01:54.950 --> 01:01:57.830
to see his way of teaching.

01:01:57.830 --> 01:02:02.330
And his pedagogical style
is indeed really unique.

01:02:02.330 --> 01:02:08.360
I felt he's really good at
making students think and feel

01:02:08.360 --> 01:02:12.510
like they discover the
concepts by themselves.

01:02:12.510 --> 01:02:16.850
And if he seems sometimes lost
in front of the blackboard,

01:02:16.850 --> 01:02:20.840
I quickly realized
it's just pretense.

01:02:20.840 --> 01:02:25.400
He knows exactly what
he's talking about.

01:02:25.400 --> 01:02:29.630
And I should say also
that, as department head,

01:02:29.630 --> 01:02:34.430
I often meet alumni, MIT Alumni,
whether they are math majors

01:02:34.430 --> 01:02:36.320
or from other disciplines.

01:02:36.320 --> 01:02:38.810
And quite often
they say, oh, I have

01:02:38.810 --> 01:02:43.100
this memorable class at MIT.

01:02:43.100 --> 01:02:45.140
The name was, uh, ah--

01:02:45.140 --> 01:02:46.370
Gil Strang.

01:02:46.370 --> 01:02:51.750
And then they say, oh, he must
be retired by now, decades ago.

01:02:51.750 --> 01:02:55.940
And I say, no, no,
he's still here.

01:02:55.940 --> 01:03:01.190
But finally, I'll be able to
say, yes, he has retired now.

01:03:01.190 --> 01:03:03.080
GILBERT STRANG: I'm
sorry to hear that.

01:03:03.080 --> 01:03:05.550
[LAUGHTER]

01:03:05.550 --> 01:03:09.140
MICHEL GOEMANS: So I've
been in this department

01:03:09.140 --> 01:03:13.370
for half of his tenure, and he
has been an amazingly pleasant

01:03:13.370 --> 01:03:13.940
colleague.

01:03:13.940 --> 01:03:15.800
He is so humble.

01:03:15.800 --> 01:03:18.950
And so after 61 years
at the Institute,

01:03:18.950 --> 01:03:21.150
we'll miss him and his teaching.

01:03:21.150 --> 01:03:23.300
But I think he fully
deserves retirement.

01:03:23.300 --> 01:03:25.640
So please join me in
congratulating Gil

01:03:25.640 --> 01:03:29.300
for his lifelong
dedication to mathematics

01:03:29.300 --> 01:03:31.400
and his education in MIT.

01:03:31.400 --> 01:03:34.706
[CHEERING, APPLAUSE]

01:03:34.706 --> 01:03:54.837


01:03:54.837 --> 01:03:56.310
GILBERT STRANG: Oh.

